post_text: THIS IS PROJECT PERIOD EXHIBITION! post_text: THIS IS PROJECT PERIOD ‚ÄúCanoe-About‚Äù Eight 7th-11th graders, one week, 60 miles, and five canoes. In West Branch Penobscot River (from Roll Dam to Forestry Point) in the deep wilderness of spectacular Maine, these kids learned to paddle - but they also learned about unplugging (no cell service whatsoever), wilderness ethics, and cooperative routines. post_text:
‚ÄúThe Charter School allowed me to grow in ways I never could‚Äôve elsewhere,‚Äù said Keith Chatinover. Thank goodness for that. MVPCS has been lucky to have Keith Chatinover as a student since 6th grade, and Middlebury College and State Rep Dylan Fernandes are lucky to lead him into his bright future. No one deserved the Massachusetts High School Activist of the Year Award more, nor the MV League of Women Voters scholarship, nor the Thomas H. Lee and Barbara F. Lee Award from the MV Permanent Endowment. Indeed, Keith‚Äôs tireless work for environmental and social justice and all he does to further the fight against gun violence, not to mention the focus and enthusiasm he brought to his learning every school day has been something to behold. The walls and the people of the Charter School will miss this human - and his relentless idealism - immensely.
Excellent photo by classmate @dashiell.rozum #seniorprofiles #mvpubliccharterschool #proud #graduation @rep.dylanfernandes @middleburycollege @leagueofwomenvoters

post_text:
Here‚Äôs to celebrating International Women‚Äôs Day yesterday, today, and EVERY DAY. We‚Äôre so proud of our girls and so grateful for our teachers and community. Some humbling and motivating statistics:
1. Globally, 65 million girls are not in school.
2. There are 31 million girls of primary school age not in school. Seventeen million of these girls will probably never attend school in their lifetimes.
3. Of the 123 million young people between the ages of 15 and 24 who cannot read or write, 61 percent of them are women.
4. There are 33 million fewer girls than boys in primary school.
5. Girls with eight years of education are four times less likely to marry as children.
6. A girl with an extra year of education can earn 20 percent more as an adult.
7. A child born to a mother who can read and write is 50 percent more likely to survive past the age of 5.
8. Educated mothers are more than twice as likely to send their children to school.
